      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Alan G. Lance Sr., the national commander of the American Legion, asserts that lifting the Pentagon's ban on homosexuals serving openly in the military is uncalled for because ''it would damage unit cohesion'' (letter, July 31).</p>
        <p>This is the same sophistical, insidious argument used to fight racial integration of the military not so very long ago. Unit cohesion is a result of first-rate training, and is a necessary component of military success no matter whose presence is allegedly causing the uproar. If military personnel cannot be taught to respect every face in the unit, whether black or white, heterosexual or homosexual, perhaps the fault lies with the unit commanders, who might not be cut out for the responsibility of disciplining troops, rather than with a policy (as yet unrealized) of military inclusiveness.</p>
        <p>DAVID WOLF  New York, July 31, 2000</p>
      </block>
